npc/ana: My name is Ana. I used to teach math at the school down the street — before it closed.
npc/ana: People think this only happens to a few weak, foolish men. Let me correct you.
npc/ana: In Indonesia, online gambling has reached millions of people. Our financial watchdog, PPATK, traced its transactions into the hundreds of trillions of rupiah — in a single year.
npc/ana: It is not just gamblers in the dark. It is students. Housewives. Drivers. Farmers. Civil servants. Even children who found the ads on their phones.
npc/ana: Most of that money comes from people who can least afford to lose it — the poor, chasing a way out that does not exist.
npc/ana: My brother Dimas was 19. "It's just math, Kak," he told me. He thought he was smart enough to beat the odds.
npc/ana: Within six months his university fund was gone. Every rupiah of it.
npc/ana: He is one number in a statistic of millions. But he is my brother.
npc/ana: That is what I need you to carry: this is not rare, and it is not a moral failing. It is a trap laid for everyone, working exactly as designed.
npc/ana: Deeper in, you'll learn what it costs and what it does to the mind. For now, just understand how wide the net is.
